<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910816-0006</DOCNO><DOCID>910816-0006.</DOCID><HL>   Seats on Information   International's Board   To Be Sought by Group   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>08/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   IINT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   A shareholder group led by New York businessman andinvestor David C. Walentas said it plans to seek three ormore seats on Information International Inc.'s 10-memberboard.   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,Mr. Walentas disclosed that the group holds about an 8% stakein the Culver City, Calif., maker of computer publishingsystems. The group said it seeks board representation, butdidn't give a reason.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Walentas couldn't be reached for elaboration.   In a letter to the company included in the filing, Mr.Walentas said he plans to attend the company's annualmeeting, set for Wednesday, and plans to nominate himself andtwo other men to the board.   In a separate SEC filing, a group including Boston-basedFMR Corp., parent of Fidelity Investments, said it reached anagreement with Information International to vote its sharesfor the company's slate of directors in exchange for a seaton the board.   John R. Kountz, an executive of a Fidelity affiliate, willbe elected to the board immediately following the annualmeeting. Mr. Kountz's group holds about a 28% stake inInformation International.   Three current directors are being nominated forre-election, the company said. Alfred L. Fenaughty,Information International president, said &quot;we feel verycomfortable&quot; that the current directors will be re-elected.   Information International's net income for fiscal year1991 ended April 30 fell 67% to $111,749, or five cents ashare, from $342,545, or 15 cents a share, a year earlier.Mr. Fenaughty said the drop reflected reductions in capitalspending by newspaper companies.</TEXT></DOC>